Java provides multiple APIs for reading files:

**`Files.readAllLines(path)`** — reads entire file into a `List<String>`. Simple but loads everything into memory.

**`Files.lines(path)`** — returns a lazy `Stream<String>`. Memory-efficient for large files.

**`BufferedReader`** — classic line-by-line reader:
```java
try (BufferedReader br = Files.newBufferedReader(path)) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) { ... }
}
```

**`Files.readString(path)`** (Java 11+) — reads entire file as a single String.

Always specify charset (default is UTF-8 in modern Java). Use try-with-resources to ensure the file is closed. Use `Paths.get()` or `Path.of()` to create `Path` objects from strings.

examples.code:
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.io.IOException;

Path path = Path.of("data.txt");
try (var lines = Files.lines(path)) {
    lines
        .filter(l -> !l.isBlank())
        .forEach(System.out::println);
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.err.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
}

