body:
`BufferedReader` wraps another `Reader` and adds a buffer, dramatically improving performance when reading character streams by reducing the number of system calls.

```java
try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
}
```

Key methods:
- `readLine()` — reads one line (returns `null` at EOF)
- `read()` — reads one character
- `read(char[], offset, len)` — bulk read into char array
- `lines()` — returns a `Stream<String>` (Java 8+)
- `skip(n)` — skips n characters
- `ready()` — true if buffer is non-empty

Prefer `Files.newBufferedReader(path, charset)` over `new BufferedReader(new FileReader(path))` because it lets you specify the charset explicitly, avoiding platform-dependent defaults.

examples.code:
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.*;

Path path = Path.of("words.txt");
try (BufferedReader br = Files.newBufferedReader(path)) {
    long count = br.lines()
        .filter(line -> line.startsWith("Java"))
        .count();
    System.out.println("Matching lines: " + count);
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}

